import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="On living people — how this archive handles privacy" description="The editorial principles by which this archive handles living individuals' personal information.">
  <article class="prose prose-stone max-w-prose">
    <h1>On living people</h1>
    <p class="text-ink/70 italic">
      The editorial principles by which this archive handles living individuals'
      personal information. Plain-language; no legal language.
    </p>

    <h2>The principle</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Living people get a light touch.</strong> The genealogical record
      is rich, but the public site is not the place to surface every detail of
      every living family member.
    </p>
    <p>The practical rules:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>No specific birth dates</strong> (day or month) for living
        people unless they have explicitly opted in. Birth year may appear in
        context for figures whose age is already public (Chuck is on the
        Stanford faculty; his year is in his university bio).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No exact home locations</strong> &mdash; street addresses,
        neighborhoods, specific towns &mdash; for living people who haven't
        opted in. Broader geography (state, country, the city of an
        on-the-record public role) may appear when it serves the narrative.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No minor children's names.</strong> Children mentioned in
        adults' obituaries or family records are referred to in general terms
        on the public site.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The address appendix is offline.</strong> Mary Eesley Bean's
        1985 family register includes a contact-address appendix. That appendix
        is kept in the private family archive; the rest of the register is
        published.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Letters that the family has marked private remain private.</strong>
        See the curation principle on the
        <a href="/docs/letters-from-vietnam/">Letters from Vietnam</a> page.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How the site enforces this</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>people</code> collection has a <code>living: true</code> flag.
      A helper called <code>publicDisplay</code> hides the header vitals
      (birth date, birth place, aka, summary) for anyone with that flag set.
      In addition, the source markdown for living-flagged pages has been
      cleaned of specific dates and locations in both frontmatter and body
      text &mdash; so that the publicly-published HTML and the underlying
      source on GitHub stay consistent.
    </p>

    <h2>The owner exception</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="/family/charles-eric-eesley/">Chuck Eesley</a>, who keeps the
      archive, has chosen to leave his own page in normal form. The general
      rule applies to everyone else with <code>living: true</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>The opt-in path</h2>
    <p>
      If you are a family member with a page here and you'd like to add detail
      &mdash; or take detail away &mdash; please contact Chuck directly. The
      site is built to be easy to update.
    </p>

    <h2>Disclosure of AI-generated content</h2>
    <p>
      Where this archive contains AI-generated visual material &mdash; for
      example the <a href="/family/zhongchu-li/">animated portrait of
      Lijie's grandfather Zhongchu Li</a>, the
      <a href="/family/zhaoxiang-zhou/">animated portrait of her grandfather
      Zhaoxiang Zhou</a>, the
      <a href="/family/ling-zhou/">animated portrait of her father Ling
      Zhou</a>, and the colorization of Robert Earl in the 1965 Stanford
      fountain photograph &mdash; the AI involvement is disclosed inline.
      The underlying still photograph is the historical artifact; the
      animation or colorization is presented as a small visual aid generated
      from it, not as a moving image of the person.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this archive exists</h2>
    <p>
      The site is the next round in a long line of family record-keeping
      &mdash; from Mary Eesley Bean's 1985 indented register, to Margaret
      "Maggie" Eesley's "Four Generations" photographic catalogue, to
      Robert Earl Wildermuth's 1990 Wildermuth/Fleming Heritage, to Dale
      Eesley's ongoing FamilySearch tree. The previous generations of
      keepers built the structured record; this site is the narrative layer
      that sits on top of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      The privacy posture is meant to keep that record open enough to be
      useful to future genealogists &mdash; the explicit audience
      <a href="/family/robert-earl-wildermuth/">Robert Earl addressed at the
      end of his memoir</a> &mdash; while keeping the lives of living family
      members in their own hands.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
